DRY principle - you give the variables a name once, in the function definition. e.g:<p><pre><code>    //decl in the header
    int pow(int exponent, int base);
</code></pre>
if you only look at the header you might think that the arguments are one way, but<p><pre><code>    //actual definition
    int pow(int base, int exponent){
      //math is correct but base <-> exponent..
    }
</code></pre>
i&#x27;m not saying i agree with this at all - it&#x27;s a contrived example..!
